Exam 1

  1. Question

    A farm produces 4 types of fruit: watermelons, mangos, persimmons, and kiwis. The fruits’ masses follow normal distributions, with parameters dependent on the type of fruit.

    Type of fruit _ _ Mean mass (g) _ _ Standard deviation of mass (g) _
    watermelons 9840 570
    mangos 301 48
    persimmons 142 15
    kiwis 81 9

    One specimen of each type is weighed. The results are shown below.

    specimen type _ _ Mass of specimen (g)
    watermelon 8740
    mango 262.1
    persimmon 160.9
    kiwi 94.23

    1. Calculate a zz score for the watermelon specimen. (Round to the nearest hundredth.)
    2. What percent of watermelons have less mass than the watermelon specimen?
    3. Calculate a zz score for the mango specimen. (Round to the nearest hundredth.)
    4. What percent of mangos have less mass than the mango specimen?
    5. Calculate a zz score for the persimmon specimen. (Round to the nearest hundredth.)
    6. What percent of persimmons have less mass than the persimmon specimen?
    7. Calculate a zz score for the kiwi specimen. (Round to the nearest hundredth.)
    8. What percent of kiwis have less mass than the kiwi specimen?
    9. The watermelon specimen is most unusually large. / The mango specimen is most unusually large. / The persimmon specimen is most unusually large. / The kiwi specimen is most unusually large.
    10. The watermelon specimen is most unusually small. / The mango specimen is most unusually small. / The persimmon specimen is most unusually small. / The kiwi specimen is most unusually small.
    11. The watermelon specimen is most typically sized. / The mango specimen is most typically sized. / The persimmon specimen is most typically sized. / The kiwi specimen is most typically sized.
    12. The watermelon specimen is most unusually sized. / The mango specimen is most unusually sized. / The persimmon specimen is most unusually sized. / The kiwi specimen is most unusually sized.

    Solution

    1. We use the formula for calculating the watermelon specimen’s zz score. z=8740−9840570=−1.93z = \frac{8740-9840}{570} = -1.93
    2. Use the zz table to find the percentile rank. P(Z<−1.93)=0.0268P(Z<-1.93) = 0.0268
    3. We use the formula for calculating the mango specimen’s zz score. z=262.1−30148=−0.81z = \frac{262.1-301}{48} = -0.81
    4. Use the zz table to find the percentile rank. P(Z<−0.81)=0.209P(Z<-0.81) = 0.209
    5. We use the formula for calculating the persimmon specimen’s zz score. z=160.9−14215=1.26z = \frac{160.9-142}{15} = 1.26
    6. Use the zz table to find the percentile rank. P(Z<1.26)=0.8962P(Z<1.26) = 0.8962
    7. We use the formula for calculating the kiwi specimen’s zz score. z=94.23−819=1.47z = \frac{94.23-81}{9} = 1.47
    8. Use the zz table to find the percentile rank. P(Z<1.47)=0.9292P(Z<1.47) = 0.9292
    9. We determine the maximum zz score is 1.471.47, which belongs to the kiwi. / . / . / .
    10. We determine the minimum zz score is −1.93-1.93, which belongs to the watermelon. / . / . / .
    11. We determine the minimum absolute zz score is 0.810.81, which belongs to the mango. / . / . / .
    12. We determine the maximum absolute zz score is 1.931.93, which belongs to the watermelon. / . / . / .

  2. Question

    Random variable YY is normally distributed with mean μ=95\mu = 95 and standard deviation σ=16\sigma = 16. Y=N(95,16)Y = \text{N}(95,\,16) Evaluate P(Y<131)P(Y < 131).


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the YY axis by adding integer multiples of 16 to 95. We know to shade toward the left because small values of YY satisfy the condition Y<131Y<131.


    We are given a specific yy value as a boundary. (Remember, for random variables we use uppercase letters, but for specific values we use lowercase.) y=131y = 131 We calculate the zz value of the boundary. z=y−μσ=131−9516=2.25\begin{aligned} z &= \frac{y-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{131-95}{16} \\\\ &= 2.25 \end{aligned}

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because P(Y<131)=P(Z<2.25)P(Y<131) ~=~ P(Z<2.25)

    So, we just need to evaluate P(Z<2.25)P(Z<2.25). To do this, you just need a zz-table.

    zz P(Z<z)P(Z<z)
    2.23 0.9871
    2.24 0.9875
    2.25 0.9878
    2.26 0.9881
    2.27 0.9884

    Thus, we find our answer. P(Y<131)=0.9878P(Y<131) = 0.9878


  3. Question

    Random variable KK is normally distributed with mean μ=230\mu = 230 and standard deviation σ=20\sigma = 20. K=N(230,20)K = \text{N}(230,\,20) Evaluate P(K>240)P(K > 240).


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the KK axis by adding integer multiples of 20 to 230. We know to shade toward the right because large values of KK satisfy the condition K>240K>240.


    We are given a specific kk value as a boundary. (Remember, for random variables we use uppercase letters, but for specific values we use lowercase.) k=240k = 240 We calculate the zz value of the boundary. z=k−μσ=240−23020=0.5\begin{aligned} z &= \frac{k-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{240-230}{20} \\\\ &= 0.5 \end{aligned}

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because P(K>240)=P(Z>0.5)P(K>240) ~=~ P(Z>0.5)

    So, we just need to evaluate P(Z>0.5)P(Z>0.5).

    To do this, you need to remember that right-area events are complementary to left-area events. P(Z>0.5)=1−P(Z<0.5)P(Z>0.5) ~=~ 1-P(Z<0.5)

    You can use a zz-table.

    zz P(Z<z)P(Z<z)
    0.48 0.6844
    0.49 0.6879
    0.5 0.6915
    0.51 0.695
    0.52 0.6985

    Thus, we find our answer. P(K>240)=1−0.6915=0.3085\begin{aligned} P(K>240) &= 1-0.6915 \\ &= 0.3085 \end{aligned}


  4. Question

    Random variable VV is normally distributed with mean μ=730\mu = 730 and standard deviation σ=200\sigma = 200. V=N(730,200)V = \text{N}(730,\,200) Evaluate P(|V−730|<90)P\left(\big|V-730\big| < 90\right). In other words, what is the probability that VV is within ±90\pm90 units from the mean?


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the VV axis by adding integer multiples of 200 to 730. We know to shade the center because values near 730 satisfy the condition |V−730|<90\big|V-730\big| < 90. We draw the boundaries at 730−90=640730-90=640 and 730+90=820730+90=820 because those are the solutions to |V−730|=90\big|V-730\big| = 90. We can also rephrase the probability.

    P(|V−730|<90)=P(640<V<820)P\left(\big|V-730\big| < 90\right) ~=~ P(640<V<820)


    We calculate the zz values of the boundaries. Left boundary: z1=640−730200=−90200=−0.45\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{640-730}{200} \\\\ &= \frac{-90}{200} \\\\ &= -0.45 \end{aligned}

    Right boundary:

    z2=820−730200=90200=0.45\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{820-730}{200} \\\\ &= \frac{90}{200} \\\\ &= 0.45 \end{aligned}

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because

    P(|V−730|<90)=P(640<V<820)=P(−0.45<Z<0.45)=P(|Z|<0.45)P\left(\big|V-730\big| < 90\right) ~=~ P(640<V<820) ~=~ P(-0.45<Z<0.45) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big|<0.45\right)

    So, we just need to evaluate P(|Z|<0.45)P(|Z|<0.45). I will also point out that 90200=0.45\frac{90}{200} = 0.45. In general, if XX is normally distributed, then: P(|X−μ|<d)=P(|Z|<dσ)P\left(\big|X-\mu\big|<d\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big| < \frac{d}{\sigma}\right)

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the zz table. (We practiced this part before.) P(|Z|<0.45)=2×P(Z<0.45)−1=2×0.6736−1=0.3472\begin{aligned} P(|Z|<0.45) &= 2 \times P(Z<0.45)-1 \\ &= 2 \times 0.6736-1 \\ &= 0.3472 \end{aligned}


  5. Question

    Random variable AA is normally distributed with mean μ=77\mu = 77 and standard deviation σ=20\sigma = 20. A=N(77,20)A = \text{N}(77,\,20) Evaluate P(|A−77|>25)P\left(\big|A-77\big| > 25\right). In other words, what is the probability that AA is outside ±25\pm25 units from the mean?


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the AA axis by adding integer multiples of 20 to 77. We know to shade the two tails because values far from 77 satisfy the condition |A−77|>25\big|A-77\big| > 25. We draw the boundaries at 77−25=5277-25=52 and 77+25=10277+25=102 because those are the solutions to |A−77|=25\big|A-77\big| = 25. We can also rephrase the probability.

    P(|A−77|>25)=P(A<52 OR A>102)P\left(\big|A-77\big| > 25\right) ~=~ P\big(A<52 \text{ OR } A>102\big)


    We calculate the zz values of the boundaries. Left boundary: z1=52−7720=−2520=−1.25\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{52-77}{20} \\\\ &= \frac{-25}{20} \\\\ &= -1.25 \end{aligned}

    Right boundary:

    z2=102−7720=2520=1.25\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{102-77}{20} \\\\ &= \frac{25}{20} \\\\ &= 1.25 \end{aligned}

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because

    P(|A−77|>25)=P(|Z|>1.25)P\left(\big|A-77\big| > 25\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big|>1.25\right)

    So, we just need to evaluate P(|Z|>1.25)P(|Z|>1.25). I will also point out that 2520=1.25\frac{25}{20} = 1.25. In general, if XX is normally distributed, then: P(|X−μ|>d)=P(|Z|>dσ)P\left(\big|X-\mu\big|>d\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big| > \frac{d}{\sigma}\right)

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the zz table. (We practiced this part before.) P(|Z|>1.25)=2−2×P(Z<1.25)=2−2×0.8944=0.2112\begin{aligned} P(|Z|>1.25) &= 2- 2 \times P(Z<1.25) \\ &= 2 - 2 \times 0.8944 \\ &= 0.2112 \end{aligned}


  6. Question

    Random variable DD is normally distributed with mean μ=180\mu = 180 and standard deviation σ=50\sigma = 50. D=N(180,50)D = \text{N}(180,\,50) Evaluate P(70<X<270)P\left(70 < X < 270\right). In other words, what is the probability that DD is between 7070 and 270270?


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the DD axis by adding integer multiples of 50 to 180. We know to shade the between 7070 and 270270 because those values satisfy the condition 70<X<27070 < X < 270.


    We calculate the zz values of the boundaries. Left boundary: z1=x1−μσ=70−18050=−2.2\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{x_1-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{70-180}{50} \\\\ &= -2.2 \end{aligned}

    Right boundary:

    z2=x2−μσ=270−18050=1.8\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{x_2-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{270-180}{50} \\\\ &= 1.8 \end{aligned}

    We rephrase our problem into a standard normal probability problem:

    P(70<X<270)=P(−2.2<Z<1.8)P\left(70 < X < 270\right) ~=~ P(-2.2<Z<1.8)

    So, we just need to evaluate P(−2.2<Z<1.8)P(-2.2<Z<1.8).

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the zz table. (We practiced this part before.) P(z1<Z<z2)=P(Z<z2)−P(Z<z1)P(−2.2<Z<1.8)=P(Z<1.8)−P(Z<−2.2)=0.9641−0.0139=0.9502\begin{aligned} P(z_1 < Z < z_2) &= P(Z<z_2) - P(Z<z1) \\ P(-2.2<Z<1.8) &= P(Z<1.8)-P(Z<-2.2)\\ &= 0.9641-0.0139 \\ &= 0.9502 \end{aligned}


  7. Question

    Random variable HH is normally distributed with mean μ=7.6\mu = 7.6 and standard deviation σ=1.9\sigma = 1.9. H=N(7.6,1.9)H = \text{N}(7.6,\,1.9) Evaluate hh such that P(H<h)=0.33P(H<h) = 0.33. In other words, determine an upper boundary such that a normal spinner with mean 7.6 and standard deviation 1.9 lands on a value less than that boundary 33% of the time.


    Solution

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the HH axis by adding integer multiples of 1.9 to 7.6. We know to shade the left because low values of HH satisfy the condition H<hH<h (regardless of the exact value of hh). We don’t know exactly where to place the boundary, but we know the left area is 0.33.

    It is helpful to know the following approximations:

    zz P(Z<z)P(Z<z)
    -3 0.001
    -2 0.023
    -1 0.159
    0 0.5
    1 0.841
    2 0.977
    3 0.999

    So, we know the zz-score is between -1 and 0. Remember, ZZ and zz always refer to the standard normal variable.


    By using the zz table we can determine zz more precisely.

    zz P(Z<z)P(Z<z)
    -0.46 0.3228
    -0.45 0.3264
    -0.44 0.33
    -0.43 0.3336
    -0.42 0.3372
    -0.45 0.3409

    Either -0.44 or -0.43 is a good estimation of zz, and either value will lead you to an acceptable answer. Using other tools, a more accurate value can be found. I will show the work with a more accurate value. z=−0.4399z=-0.4399

    We now convert the zz score into a hh score. h=μ+zσ=7.6+(−0.4399)(1.9)=6.764\begin{aligned} h &= \mu+z\sigma \\ &= 7.6+(-0.4399)(1.9) \\ &= 6.764 \end{aligned}

    We can also visualize this with a spinner.
